<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1895-09-04T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1895-09-04T00:00:00-05:00" n="75" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d75">
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Willis</persName> to Mr.
                                    <persName type="to">Adee</persName>.</hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener><seg rendition="#center">[Abstract.]</seg></opener>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Legation of the United States</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">Honolulu</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1895-09-04"><hi rend="italic">September 4,
                                    1895</hi></date>. (Received Sept. 18.)</dateline>
                            <seg rendition="#left">No. 133.]</seg></opener>
                        <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: The Government has pardoned 44 political
                            prisoners connected with the recent uprising. All of these are Hawaiians
                            or half-castes. <pb facs="0131" n="865" xml:id="pg_865"/> Of these, the
                            principal are Jonah C. Kalanianaole (“Prince Cupid”); Carl Widemann, son
                            of Hon. H. A. Widemann, late commissioner to Washington of the ex-Queen,
                            and the four Lane brothers.</p>
                        <p>I am, etc.,</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Albert S. Willis.</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>